# Manifest validation deps used by plugin-json-validate.yml and the
# jsonschema check in release-reusable.yml. Both call sites share this
# lock to avoid drift between PR-time and tag-cut validation.
#
# Regenerate the locked requirements.txt on Python 3.14 (matches both the
# `actions/setup-python` version pinned in the consuming workflows and the
# interpreter Dependabot's updater image runs). Run it from INSIDE this
# directory, with these flags — that is verbatim what Dependabot invokes, so
# its bump PR rewrites only the dependency lines and not the header:
#   cd .github-deps/validate
#   python3.14 -m venv .tmp/pip-compile-venv
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip install pip-tools
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip-compile \
#     --generate-hashes --no-emit-index-url --strip-extras \
#     --output-file=requirements.txt requirements.in
# No --allow-unsafe: this lock pins no unsafe package (setuptools / pip), so the
# flag adds nothing and Dependabot's write path omits it.
# Deliberately UNPINNED here. pip-compile writes the exact version (with hashes)
# into requirements.txt, which is the lock; pinning the same version again in
# this file is not belt-and-braces, it is a wall Dependabot cannot climb: it
# bumps by running `pip-compile -P <dep>==<new>` against this file, and a `==`
# here makes that resolution impossible. It did — every pip update job failed on
# it from at least 2026-06-29 (#186). The exact version lives in the lock, where
# it belongs.
#
# That was only the first of two walls. Unpinning fixed the resolution and the
# job then failed one stage later, at submission: these locks used to live under
# `.github/`, and Dependabot's backend grants the `workflows` write scope only to
# the `github-actions` ecosystem, so a pip job proposing a change there is
# refused with `400 The request contains invalid or unauthorized changes` (#191).
# Hence `.github-deps/` rather than `.github/requirements/`. Do not move these
# back under `.github/`.
jsonschema
requests
